The Haitian Creole (HC) situation is a bit different because of diglossia.  One area were interference showed up was in topic comment constructions, like: 
It is more important, because of American history

The bottom line is that interference works in two directions--unless the tutor is aware that systematic interference is at work rather than simple "error," she or he will not preserve the tuteee's intended meaning.  Arbitrarily changing a passage to the nearest "correct" English structure can only confuse matters for both parties by changing (nearly always for the worse) the author's argument structure without the author or the tutor understanding why.  This obviously leads to frustration on all sides.  Tutors do not need to be fluent in the systems of their tutees, but they do need to make sure somehow that the tutees' intended meanings are respected and preserved, or else changed with full knowledge on both sides.  This can usually be done by verbally rephrasing a passage, or even drawing the relations between the phrases or words, and then asking the tutee if that is what she or he means.  If it is not, explore how the meaning changes to give the students more Academese frames to work with. Most of the problems are not with meaning but with using grammatical constructions to show relations.   One way to do this is to break complex sentences down into their simplest forms and then reconnect them.  Interference takes place largely on the level of how complex structures are put together--this may be at the level of 
--	sounds, such as "would of" for academese "would have;" it may be at the level of words, such as the use of serial verbs where academese would call for a verb and an adverb or prepositional phrase; 
--	grammar, such as those for agreement in number between nouns and verbs; 
--	clause structure, as in the "PRO-drop" and "BE-deletion" situations;
--	the sentence, as in Topic-Comment structures; 
--	discourse, as in the use of unmarked verbs for simple past once time has been established.  
--	style, which has not been discussed here.
To the extent that interference takes place at the level of intended meaning, we have left the territory of ESL tutoring per se.  From there, we enter into whorfian cultural relativity and deconstructionism.  In the territory of linguistic interference with subjective meaning, we can't do anything but stare in mute foucaultion unapprehension.  These issues might best be dealt with elsewhere in the academy.  Within ESL tutorials, dealing constructively with other issues of linguistic interference will simply allow the student--and her or his teachers--to engage in everyday academic matters of content and meaning without unnecessary distortions getting in the way.  


conclude:
Approach A: Fix what they do to make it right in Academese
Approach B: Find out what they mean and figure out ways to express such things in Academese.
